## Mike Hernandez – Facilities Technician (Maintenance & Operations Tech)

### Background
- **Education:** Trade certification (HVAC, electrical, plumbing) or equivalent experience
- **Experience:** 5–20 years in building maintenance; may have worked commercial before K‑12
- **Role:** Field tech responsible for mechanical, electrical, plumbing, and building system repairs
- **District Assignment:** Responsible for 2–6 buildings depending on district size
- **Schedule:** 6:00 AM – 2:30 PM typical; on-call for emergencies

### Daily Responsibilities
- Receive and complete **work orders** for repairs, preventive maintenance, and inspections
- Locate and service equipment using **building drawings and asset records**
- Document completed work, parts used, and asset condition
- Access specs, manuals, and **repair history** for building systems on site
- Respond to **emergency calls** (leaks, HVAC failures, electrical issues, safety hazards)

### Perspective on Facilities Suite
**Location and information obsessed.**
- Needs to find the **right asset in the right room in minutes**, not wander buildings guessing
- Wants mobile access to **drawings with assets pinned to location** — this is his map
- Work Orders must show **full context**: what's wrong, where it is, what was done before, and what parts he might need
- Offline access is non-negotiable — many mechanical rooms, basements, and older buildings have no connectivity

### AI Perspective & Concerns
**"Just get me the info I need faster":**
- Would welcome AI that **surfaces repair history and suggested actions** when he opens a work order
- Interested in AI that identifies **recurring issues** on an asset so he can recommend replacement instead of another patch
- Doesn't want to type long descriptions — voice-to-text or smart dropdowns would be ideal
- Suspicious of AI that tells him how to do his trade — he knows HVAC, he needs information, not instruction

**Key AI Questions:**
- Can I voice-dictate my work order notes instead of typing on a phone in a boiler room?
- Will the system show me what was done on this unit last time without scrolling through months of records?
- Can AI tell me if this unit has hit end-of-life based on repair frequency and cost?
- Does it work when I'm in a basement with no cell signal?

### Decision Criteria
1. **Speed to information**: asset location, history, and specs in under 30 seconds
2. **Mobile-first**: works on a phone with gloves, in poor lighting, and with spotty connectivity
3. **Offline capability**: must function in low/no connectivity environments
4. **Minimal data entry**: smart defaults, dropdowns, and voice input over free-text typing
5. **Accuracy**: what the system says matches what's physically in the building

### Pain Points
- Paper work orders or desktop-only systems that don't go into the field
- Walking buildings trying to find equipment that's not labeled or mapped
- Repair histories that live in someone's head, not in a system
- Duplicate work because previous repair notes weren't documented
- Being sent to a job without knowing what parts to bring

### Working Conditions Context
- Physically demanding: climbing ladders, crawling in mechanical spaces, carrying tools
- Constantly moving between buildings — windshield time is real
- Emergencies interrupt planned maintenance daily
- Works alone most of the time; needs to be self-sufficient with information

### What Would Make Our Solution Valuable
1. Mobile work order app: receive, view, update, and close from the field
2. Drawings with asset pins: tap a room, see every piece of equipment and its history
3. Work order context: problem description + asset history + last repair + parts likely needed
4. Voice-to-text for work order notes and completion comments
5. Offline mode that syncs when back in connectivity
6. Photo documentation: snap a picture of the issue and attach to the work order

### Red Flags That Would Kill a Proposal
- Desktop-only system with no real mobile app
- No offline capability
- Requires extensive typing on a phone to complete a work order
- Drawings that are static PDFs rather than interactive, searchable maps
- Asset data that's wrong or out of date — he'll stop trusting and stop using it

